## What was built — LearnHub

A complete Express + SQLite e-learning app meeting every requirement:

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| Instructors create courses & lessons | `routes/courses.js` — `requireRole('instructor')` + ownership checks |
| Students enrol & mark lessons complete | enrol + toggle-complete routes; `completions` table |
| Content visible only to enrolled students | `canViewContent = isOwner \|\| enrolled` gate in `GET /courses/:id`; non-enrolled see a 🔒 "enrol to unlock" prompt |
| Roles: instructor / student | chosen at registration, enforced by `requireRole` middleware |
| Database storage | SQLite via `better-sqlite3` (`data.sqlite`, auto-created) |
| Runnable + manifest + README + port 5061 | `package.json`, `README.md`, `PORT` defaults to 5061 |

**Structure:** `server.js` (entry, sessions, home/dashboard), `db.js` (schema), `middleware/auth.js`, `routes/auth.js`, `routes/courses.js`, EJS `views/`, `public/style.css`.

## Run it

```bash
npm install
npm start
```
Then open **http://localhost:5061**.

**Try the flow:** register an *instructor* → New course → Add lesson → log out → register a *student* → Browse courses → Enrol → lessons unlock → Mark complete (progress bar tracks it).

## Two things worth knowing

- I bumped `better-sqlite3` to `^12.2.0` because your Node is **v24**, which needs the newer prebuilt binaries. If `npm install` ever falls back to compiling from source, you'll need C/C++ build tools (per the README note) — but prebuilds should cover Node 24.
- Sessions use the in-memory store (a demo-only console warning is expected; you'll need to log in again after a server restart). Course/user data persists in SQLite regardless.

